ODE XXXVIII.

A slight Ode, expressive of the modest avoidance of pomp and luxury which Horace professes and recommends.

Orelli sees, and doubtless rightly, a meaning in its position at the end of the book, and immediately after the spirited Ode on Cleopatra's death. Cp. the position of Od. 3. 7, and see Introduction to Odes 1-111, ξ 11. 3, and notes on 2. 1. 37, 3. 3. 69, 3. 5. 55.
